[{"id":30592,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"124\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/61ec244d-3b36-4df2-a582-c1d2bf640864-image.png\" width=\"276\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"128\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48db4511-c77e-4890-b948-ef1c1b2749b9-image.png\" width=\"279\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"124\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/045c804a-037d-47e3-a433-4e7a0cbaa5c7-image.png\" width=\"220\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"121\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8545725f-dc78-4ae4-9a7f-5caa4a9c9cfe-image.png\" width=\"279\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img height=\"100\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6d0ce192-0e43-45cd-ac26-b7a148d458a2-image.png\" width=\"828\" /><br /><br />Addition of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is an electrophilic addition. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math> increases the electron density on the left benzene ring, whereas the carbonyl group decreases the charge density of the right benzene group. As a result, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is added to the left benzene group due to higher charge density.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30417,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect"],"answer":0,"solution":"Statement I: Benzene reacts with nitrating mixture ($conc. HNO_3 + conc. H_2SO_4$) to form nitrobenzene. However, nitrobenzene is highly deactivated due to the strong electron-withdrawing $-I$ and $-M$ effects of the $-NO_2$ group. Friedel-Crafts reactions (alkylation or acylation) do not occur on strongly deactivated rings like nitrobenzene. Thus, nitrobenzene will not react with $CH_3COCl/AlCl_3$ to give m-nitroacetophenone. Statement I is incorrect.<br><br>Statement II: The $-NO_2$ group is a meta-directing group because it withdraws electron density from the ortho and para positions more than from the meta position. It is also a deactivating group as it reduces the overall electron density of the benzene ring, making it less reactive towards electrophilic aromatic substitution. Statement II is correct.<br><br>Therefore, Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30395,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":3,"solution":"Statement I is false because Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate produces ethane, not methane. The reaction is: $2\\text{CH}_3\\text{COONa} + 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\xrightarrow{\\text{Electrolysis}} \\text{CH}_3-\\text{CH}_3 + 2\\text{CO}_2 + \\text{H}_2 + 2\\text{NaOH}$. Decarboxylation of sodium ethanoate and the reaction of $\\text{CH}_3\\text{MgBr}$ with water do produce methane.<br><br>Statement II is true because the simplest unsaturated hydrocarbon is ethene ($\\text{C}_2\\text{H}_4$), which upon hydrogenation yields ethane, meaning methane cannot be prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons. Additionally, the Wurtz reaction involves the coupling of two alkyl halide molecules to form an alkane with at least two carbon atoms ($2\\text{RX} + 2\\text{Na} \\rightarrow \\text{R}-\\text{R} + 2\\text{NaX}$), so methane cannot be prepared by this method.<br><br>Therefore, Statement I is false but Statement II is true.<br><br>Answer: Statement I is false but Statement II is true","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30522,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c3493ed3-db35-418d-8613-c853193dc398-image.png\" style=\"width: 282px; height: 104px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0605c4f7-2f8b-48d1-8b2f-ac4bd7e10d7a-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 104px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ebaecf43-62f7-4eee-8c34-3a5e4bbaf6de-image.png\" style=\"width: 210px; height: 95px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa074919-6fac-4be3-9867-30946a38db3d-image.png\" style=\"width: 137px; height: 145px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b8407213-0f8b-414a-a10b-2c6f762c8f97-image.png\" style=\"width: 531px; height: 216px;\" /></p><p>At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> thermodynamicaly controlled Product is formed as major product.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30599,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N3n3YUKr3Y2tZRnlJdLs77mU21WfFTpkY9DUNIaR3fM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/T7YeF4Wsy4mAmm_y00NJUfJ73jPAqenUuiJbBVHp94o.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fsgiCzmnaQyyDPUSzemMop2HC2veLjSVaOvn-bVZIi0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5tLRv3cvp9dw6Nzr6ghwS0m1S95xugrJ27UA-mCM6uw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Here dehydrohalogenation goes by $\\mathrm{E1cB}$ and most stable carbanion formation is favoured in (a).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":30458,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10c99310-0d35-44a0-a79d-8f433631195b.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 197px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e83ff9f3-dd71-4404-a88b-1dd71d59f0b3.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 191px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5cc9dc4c-38c3-4dec-9be8-b51c4d8a1fd6.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 212px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6df60ca3-0fd8-4af9-a21d-a896c7ee5868.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 233px;\"/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>During an electrophilic addition reactions double bonds donate lone pair electrons to an electrophile.</p><p>Markovnikov's Rule: The addition of a proton <span style=\"background-color:null;\">acid</span> to the double bond of an alkene results in a product with the acid hydrogen bound to the carbon atom that already has the greater number of hydrogen attached.</p><p>In the given reaction electrophile <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> adds to the double bond, a carbocation is formed. Then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is added at the electron deficient carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/88865b3e-9c8b-4648-bcc8-41fc49554fe5.png\" style=\"width: 767px; height: 207px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30565,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/078d9c0b-14ce-444d-ae52-01e1553bf20d-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 147px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/18176eae-0580-4bd6-ac81-55c3cc0e31e6-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 142px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9dc9a58e-983c-4fb0-8940-da380fc6c0e0-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 190px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ee1d0790-3f14-4203-a52b-14380cd76136-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 185px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;This is electrophilic substitution reaction which is determine by electronic effect of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OH</mi><mo>\\</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>\\</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14570784-5d58-4f77-9bbc-ba7fa1461a6e-image.png\" style=\"width: 531px; height: 201px;\" /></p><p>Electrophilic attacks in influence of activating group&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;so it is attached at para position with respect to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;group.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30446,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Cb6KvLctinSUCIKOb0fjzFxuYBLA8RGC89d7q8FTTug.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30398,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":3,"solution":"The structure of \"S\" is 2-methylcyclopent-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid.<br><br>Since \"S\" is obtained by the acidification of the product from the iodoform reaction of \"R\", \"R\" must contain a methyl ketone group ($-COCH_3$). The iodoform reaction converts the $-COCH_3$ group into a $-COOH$ group alongside the formation of a yellow precipitate of iodoform ($CHI_3$). Therefore, the structure of \"R\" is 1-acetyl-2-methylcyclopentene.<br><br>\"R\" is formed by the intramolecular aldol condensation of \"Q\". Performing a retro-aldol condensation on \"R\" by cleaving the double bond in the cyclopentene ring yields octane-2,7-dione as \"Q\" ($CH_3-CO-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CO-CH_3$).<br><br>\"Q\" is obtained by the ozonolysis of \"P\". To determine the structure of \"P\", we perform retro-ozonolysis by removing the oxygen atoms from the two carbonyl groups of \"Q\" and connecting the corresponding carbon atoms with a double bond. Connecting the C2 and C7 carbons forms a six-membered ring with methyl groups at the double bond.<br><br>Thus, \"P\" is 1,2-dimethylcyclohexene.<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30575,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"136\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3392565-e9ef-4325-9fbe-38284bc9c74a-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"272\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"69\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15b7afbc-6951-463c-b779-08579fbf9a5a-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"286\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"113\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/280e816c-83a2-4812-ba82-40eb96127621-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"264\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"118\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8d76452-0a68-4ed5-82ce-b97f84aa97fa-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"259\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>EtOK is potassium ethylene oxide and it is colourless gas and is liquid at low temperatures and is highly flammable i.e. that catches fire easily and undergoes alkylation reactions with many organic compounds and EtOH is the ethanol.</p><p>The heating&nbsp;of 2-chloro-1-phenylbutane&nbsp; with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>EtOK</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>EtOH</mi></math>gives&nbsp;X&nbsp;as the major product. Reaction&nbsp;X&nbsp;with&nbsp;H<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>OAc</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>followed by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;gives&nbsp;Y&nbsp;as the major product.&nbsp;Y&nbsp;is 1-phenylbutanol.</p><p><img height=\"178\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1f126db-30fd-46a5-8d02-667603c5be0a-image.png\" width=\"972\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30559,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>)</mo><mi>CH</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d5306685-d2d2-4355-a34c-c8df2e802358-image.png\" style=\"width: 689px; height: 77px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30490,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/38d60ca5-ccb6-4ddd-9d27-6382e0094f52-9894252.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 316px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f3706eb5-86e0-40a0-9b03-cdc96f60b704-9894252_B.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 193px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15b0390c-54b7-439c-8e70-a14efeadddf4-9894252_C.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 144px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eb4e1a9b-c79e-44d6-b332-55cdcf84ca6d-9894252_D.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 153px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Aromatic nucleophilic substitution reaction takes place via the formation of a&nbsp;carbanion intermediate. Hence, the rate of reaction depends on the stability of the carbanion.</p><p>Electron withdrawing effect can stabilise the carbanion. The Electron withdrawing nature of the nitro group will be minimum at the meta position.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hence the correct answer is</p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a98a1d7f-2da1-4ed2-870f-4e22e8c18e97-9894252_D.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 205px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30484,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#160;alc&#160;</mtext><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>LiqNH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mtext>, alc&#160;</mtext><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Lindlar Catalyst</p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>aqKOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;Lindlar Catalyst","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, aq <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>LiqNH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A trans alkene can be converted to a vicinal dihalide through a halogenation reaction. The vicinal dihalide can undergo double elimination to afford an alkyne. The alkyne can undergo partial reduction to give a cis alkene.</p><p>The reagents needed to convert&nbsp;trans<i><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>Ph</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math></i>&nbsp;to&nbsp;cis-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>Ph</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;are shown in the reaction scheme below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f915bf6b-e308-4d86-ad84-ed0ebbb3f799-9896079.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 431px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30463,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CH</mi></math> reacts with sodium an intermediate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CNa</mi></math> is formed which on further reaction with propyl bromide gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msub><mi>CCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> as the product. The second step of the reaction follows, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> mechanism.</p><p>The reaction is as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eeb0ea7a-8cf1-486d-9f33-ce15143a5e9c.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 205px;\"/></p><p>Hence in the above reaction,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math></p><p>Hence option A is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30396,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"Statement I:<br>When $3$-phenylpropene reacts with $HBr$, protonation of the alkene occurs to form a secondary carbocation.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH_2-CH=CH_2 + H^+ \\rightarrow C_6H_5-CH_2-CH^+-CH_3$<br><br>This secondary carbocation undergoes a $1,2$-hydride shift to form a more stable, resonance-stabilized benzylic carbocation.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH_2-CH^+-CH_3 \\rightarrow C_6H_5-CH^+-CH_2-CH_3$<br><br>The bromide ion then attacks this benzylic carbocation to form the major product, $1$-bromo-$1$-phenylpropane.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH^+-CH_2-CH_3 + Br^- \\rightarrow C_6H_5-CH(Br)-CH_2-CH_3$<br><br>The carbon atom bonded to the bromine is attached to four different groups: a phenyl group ($-C_6H_5$), an ethyl group ($-CH_2CH_3$), a hydrogen atom ($-H$), and a bromine atom ($-Br$). Thus, it is a chiral carbon. The product is a secondary alkyl bromide. Therefore, Statement I is true.<br><br>Statement II:<br>The Sandmeyer reaction involves treating a diazonium salt with $Cu(I)$ salts ($CuCl$, $CuBr$, $CuCN$) to prepare aryl chlorides, aryl bromides, and aryl cyanides, respectively.<br><br>The Gattermann reaction involves treating a diazonium salt with copper powder ($Cu$) and halogen acids ($HCl$, $HBr$) to prepare aryl chlorides and aryl bromides. Aryl cyanides are not prepared using the Gattermann reaction. Therefore, Statement II is false.<br><br>Conclusion: Statement I is true but Statement II is false.<br><br>Answer: Statement I is true but Statement II is false","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30544,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Benzene is an aromatic compound which shows the characteristic reaction of electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions. This is because the reaction is initiated by an electrophile.</p><p>Benzene reacts with&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>â€‹Cl&nbsp;in presence of anhydrous&nbsp;AlCl<sub>3</sub>â€‹&nbsp;to give Toulene. This is fridel crafts Alkylation and an electrophillic substitution.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1cbb360-b07a-4b6a-b656-1f002da56617-image.png\" style=\"width: 298px; height: 350px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30513,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PCC</mi></math> oxidation","Ozonolysis","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math> followed by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PCC</mi></math> oxidation","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math>, hydrolysis followed by oxidation by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/53792b6f-6d93-4a02-ab07-0efb851fa0bf-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 81px;\" /></p><p>First step of the reaction involves hydroboration oxidation and second step involves oxidation of primary alcoholic group by using PCC.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30422,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QSFk2GUrY99AMDep8n8SySL4Eu28OVqcq5nJvt5a5i0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />$\\Rightarrow$ Number of $\\mathrm{sp}^2 \\mathrm{C}$-atoms in product $\\mathrm{D}=7","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30516,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> identical mesomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> mesomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> racemic and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7f62a3a6-67e0-46f9-b5e3-6e9b0c245225-image.png\" style=\"width: 490px; height: 170px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30514,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e468a28c-c558-43d9-b609-484022552a77-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 98px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a4d84947-878e-47df-8840-6b38c4249aac-image.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 77px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f15edc4f-4b78-4250-84aa-a692f64019d6-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 89px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9d1e60de-d982-4070-8e27-1ec7a786bf6b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 97px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a768107f-9694-4157-bc21-63b89b832828-6c52b7a3-7a46-4f6a-818f-b96b15fde1ef-image.png\" style=\"width: 553px; height: 148px;\" /></p><p>In first step nitration of benzene ring will take place at para position, since ethyl group is ortho-para directing in nature.&nbsp;</p><p>Then halogenation&nbsp;reaction will take place at benzyl position followed by dehydrohalogenation&nbsp;reaction with alcoholic KOH.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30594,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math><mi>β</mi></math> - hydrogen","<math><mi>δ</mi></math> - hydrogen","<math><mi>α</mi></math> -hydrogen","<math><mi>γ</mi></math> - hydrogen"],"answer":3,"solution":"Allylic radial is more stable due to resonance.<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>∝</mo></math> Stability of free radical","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30466,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e1b17ea1-b465-457b-8ebf-bec07c8ffb3e.png\" style=\"width: 399px; height: 242px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/609b992a-1ab4-4d91-8e64-d552b35a8298.png\" style=\"width: 380px; height: 253px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1d34b27-9058-47bf-8242-706c768ab54a.png\" style=\"width: 480px; height: 186px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/328d5b18-0f4d-4253-a2e9-5c910f049801.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 248px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The allylic position is a carbon position present adjacent to the carbon-carbon double bonds. The allylic carbon is attached to a carbon atom that forms a double bond with a different carbon atom. A substitution could be a reaction during which a group in an organic molecule is replaced with another group.</p><p>When the halogen concentration is low enough, alkenes containing allylic hydrogen undergo substitution at the allylic position rather than addition at the double bond. The product is an allylic halide (halogen on carbon next to double bond carbons), which is acquired through a radical chain mechanism.</p><p>When cyclohexene reacts with Chlorine in the presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>, the electrophilic addition reaction takes place at double bond, which results in a dichloro product, here it is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dicholorocyclohexane.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0211780e-12b0-4e9b-93c4-7fe4c6bb7ec8.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 306px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the correct answer is D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30580,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Rate of <math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> substitution reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math> charge density on benzene ring<br />Electron releasing group; increasing the rate of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> ; halogen has <math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> so deactivating group &amp; but show <math><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> but <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d3407106-28c9-4ff0-9a76-4b8626ad319c-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 60px;\" />show <math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> so less deactivating group only<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/73dc4723-300b-44a6-ad08-285db9501917-image13.png\" /><br />Reactivity order is:<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48c233c2-e3ed-41a1-99d4-19354bb6788d-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 126px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30545,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ffc4170c-cdc9-47c8-910e-9df9dc1205c0-image.png\" style=\"width: 88px; height: 97px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/58130738-1de8-459c-8b95-aff70eb98f11-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 102px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c0774cc-be0a-4be1-b4b9-75e8381b8e53-image.png\" style=\"width: 86px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4b1757fa-a565-4a80-93a0-1a7367a8c9f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 101px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2676d41b-acb6-4db1-9b91-7171f20a5c7d-cba036a1-eaa7-47cb-80b8-4e29afdf4379-image.png\" style=\"width: 331px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mo</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>773</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> temperature and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></math>&nbsp;-atm pressure is aromatizing agent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30515,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8afa533-aab9-49d5-b8b1-8a3e2785a249-e32c4bc7-b396-4b45-9ac2-d07d92218b57-image.png\" style=\"width: 348px; height: 194px;\" /></p><p>So, there are&nbsp;total of two&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybrid carbon in the final product.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Cannizaro's reaction","Rosenmund reduction","Wolf-Kishner reduction","Clemmenson reduction"],"answer":3,"solution":"The reaction given is a Clemenson reduction.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30547,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dcde193a-c11b-48cd-9df8-1405872a190a-image.png\" style=\"width: 319px; height: 148px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd9a45f9-a674-41e8-9e70-7f55a07312bb-d1376a72-9421-4807-9b0b-e16465a4b6c7-image.png\" style=\"width: 270px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/336786bc-e6e1-4691-9124-768430769d28-image.png\" style=\"width: 324px; height: 148px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4b8c2642-8ad8-4ac7-a315-643d86a1502b-image.png\" style=\"width: 324px; height: 149px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/88ad7a6f-662b-4258-9b63-e852d9899511-674b0398-765e-417a-b395-79fb9e354658-a41f895f-1e26-47a7-9524-6184cb2662da-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 109px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>&nbsp;1st reaction Markovnikov&#39;s&nbsp;addition of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;on double bond while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi><mrow><mi>nd</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup></math> reaction is halide substitution by&nbsp;Finkelstein reaction.</p><p>Finkelstein reaction: An S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction in which one halogen atom (the leaving group) is replaced by iodide&nbsp;(the nucleophile).</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VmCW6VD9eCYZ5i-o1YTU32gofbBLs7CoGamLHL8ixM0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/36jJm1RnGZT-NNvqYkhmVvU66Mfd2iXktZG9YIaYeco.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yGiXCZsHAlcFldVav5sy6dARn1TmnM9nfiYFW4ZD1jc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WxHsauI_3MNcyYYi1lazndfA7BZ1uA_q5wlIjHM15p0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/E-vR9hlmuVkzvtszlt7wib-ekwZv27HRSGwSgO2UrLc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":30603,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Sn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Pd</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>liq</mi><mo>.</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266686.jpg\" style=\"width: 293px; height: 60px;\" /><br />Birch reduction is anti-addition. So trans alkene will be produced.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30469,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3aeb3488-2ef7-4ec6-9db9-19448da632e3.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 127px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ec5c816-5949-4e18-be51-f2ee5fa4fad8.png\" style=\"width: 262px; height: 172px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c87f037e-5866-4261-91a0-1c2c0e8e08bf.png\" style=\"width: 273px; height: 136px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cb0f8b00-66a3-479d-a1be-261d617c7d93.png\" style=\"width: 355px; height: 139px;\"/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>During the reaction, first addition of water takes place according to Markownikoff's rule, alcohol is formed, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> acts as an oxidising agents which converts alcohol into ketone, then Wolf Kishner reduction occurs.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/acef85d2-00e3-4c5c-8a36-c3ea1dc1953a.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 266px;\"/></p><p>Hence option A is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30631,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["activates the ring towards electrophilic substitution","renders the ring basic","deactivates the ring towards nucleophilic substitution","deactivates the ring towards electrophilic substitution"],"answer":3,"solution":"$-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ group shows $-\\mathrm{M}$ effect, so withdraws the electron density from the ring and hence deactivate the ring towards electrophilic aromatic substitution.\nHence, (D) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":30423,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tz5Nc0BKJUZO_OoT-ZgZzUwNPP6u8LpMOR59IvASKHk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HsrvoxzdgrO-v22rL2PoyMEAhJ4kuCdTkm1ZmagdqXE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />St-I : Correct statement<br />St-II : In correct statement because product has chiral centre.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30607,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image17-6f6916b8-33b4-4242-8370-5bd33a33241c.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image18-cd524215-6988-4b9c-8979-254956320482.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image19-6b682e0e-9e50-4fe0-8293-e106836cf9b1.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image20-4af75e1b-fbfc-4aa5-9579-ae7d88e91198.jpg\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In the given sequence, the succinic anhydride in the presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;reacts with methoxy benzene to give the following product.<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d8062574-11cd-4247-bb0f-3993016de8d6-3.PNG\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 169px;\" /></p><p>In the second step of the sequence, the compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;undergoes Clemmenson&#39;s reduction, resulting in the formation of:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6496f49f-738c-426f-be88-104c9ff0b434-4.PNG\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 155px;\" /></p><p>Overall reaction would be.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/habffwqweyr.JPG\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 94px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30526,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math><br />(ii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>,<br />(iii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math><br />(iv) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math><br />(ii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math><br />(iii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math><br />(iv) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br />(ii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math><br />(iii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo